for transit buses for the public.

00:33:35.848 --> 00:33:39.030
What is the best way
to enter dates, times,

00:33:39.030 --> 00:33:43.280
directions if you use alt text
to describe a map?"

00:33:44.360 --> 00:33:47.724
Alice: Well,
maps are very complex visual content,

00:33:47.724 --> 00:33:51.474
so I refer you
to a very incredible resource

00:33:52.244 --> 00:33:56.827
on the W3C website that is called
"alt decision tree,"

00:33:57.586 --> 00:34:02.389
which explains how to properly write
alt text for different types of images.

00:34:02.389 --> 00:34:04.175
This is very useful

00:34:04.175 --> 00:34:06.758
In general, for maps, the rule,

00:34:07.595 --> 00:34:13.512
the best practice would be to surely
describe the map in the alt text,

00:34:13.955 --> 00:34:19.803
but explain all the contexts of the visual
that we are seeing in clear,

00:34:19.803 --> 00:34:22.188
in the paragraph, in the page.

00:34:22.188 --> 00:34:27.567
Don't try to write like a romance
with your alt text to describe a map,

00:34:27.567 --> 00:34:33.151
but use the rest of the page in clear
to explain what's happening,

00:34:34.387 --> 00:34:38.324
what we can see in the visual
because the balance

00:34:38.324 --> 00:34:41.573
between writing effective alt text
and alt text

00:34:41.573 --> 00:34:44.240
that are too long is a bit tiny.

00:34:47.063 --> 00:34:50.663
We have to find a nice balance
between the two things.

00:34:50.663 --> 00:34:53.639
If you have complex content to describe,

00:34:53.639 --> 00:34:58.722
better to do that on the page
and not in the alt text field.

00:34:59.121 --> 00:35:00.693
Marina: Okay.

00:35:00.693 --> 00:35:05.443
I think this piggybacks off
of descriptiveness from Sam.

00:35:06.829 --> 00:35:12.244
"How descriptive should alt text be
for documentation and how-to posts?

00:35:12.244 --> 00:35:14.911
The images show navigation steps

00:35:15.694 --> 00:35:19.190
that are written
in the text above the image."

00:35:19.190 --> 00:35:19.859
Alice: Okay.

00:35:19.859 --> 00:35:22.924
In this case,
I would avoid to repeat the same things,

00:35:22.924 --> 00:35:26.674
the instructions that we are given
in the documentation.

00:35:26.674 --> 00:35:32.007
Maybe I usually write alt text
like screenshots of this feature

00:35:33.195 --> 00:35:38.912
and then I will explain the features
in the content of the how-to post,

00:35:38.912 --> 00:35:40.072
for example.

00:35:40.072 --> 00:35:44.847
Let's try not to replicate the text
of the alt text in the instructions

00:35:44.847 --> 00:35:46.149
that were already given.

00:35:46.149 --> 00:35:51.063
Just imagine the alt text as part
of the reading experience of people.

00:35:51.063 --> 00:35:54.031
You don't want to read
the same sentence twice.

00:35:54.031 --> 00:35:58.781
That's the criteria
we should use when writing alt text.

00:36:00.093 --> 00:36:01.544
Marina: Great.

00:36:01.544 --> 00:36:04.044
This one is from Shauna.

00:36:04.869 --> 00:36:06.799
"What are the general guidelines you go by

00:36:06.799 --> 00:36:10.848
when deciding whether
to leave the alt text empty?

00:36:10.848 --> 00:36:15.176
If you have a page of people's mugshots
with their names under their photos,

00:36:15.176 --> 00:36:18.034
do you add their names
to the alt text too?

00:36:18.034 --> 00:36:21.878
When do you decide
to include gender or race or not?"

00:36:21.878 --> 00:36:23.103
Alice: Very.

00:36:23.103 --> 00:36:25.591
Marina: Yes, I had to think about how
to describe my headshot

00:36:25.591 --> 00:36:27.779
for this conference too.

00:36:27.779 --> 00:36:30.279
Alice: Exactly.
Marina: How descriptive should I be?

00:36:30.318 --> 00:36:32.661
Alice: Exactly That's a nice thing.

00:36:32.661 --> 00:36:38.828
The organizer team did let us describe
our pictures for today's streaming

00:36:44.357 --> 00:36:48.555
It's a very nice question
and also not controversial,

00:36:48.555 --> 00:36:50.402
but there is a lot of debate on it

00:36:50.402 --> 00:36:54.485
because the rule says
that decorative pictures,

00:36:56.199 --> 00:37:00.293
decorative images shouldn't be described
with an alt text,

00:37:00.293 --> 00:37:04.376
should stay empty
with the alt text field empty.

00:37:06.693 --> 00:37:09.758
There is also that criteria
that what is pleasable,

00:37:09.758 --> 00:37:14.424
what is enjoyable
as a decorative content on a web page

00:37:14.978 --> 00:37:21.478
for sighted users should also be enjoyable
for people with visual impairment.

00:37:21.629 --> 00:37:27.462
Again, the baseline here, the line,
the differentiation line is tiny.

00:37:29.033 --> 00:37:35.533
For example, if we are talking about
the little decorative images of an icon,

00:37:35.541 --> 00:37:39.424
which is already explained
in the rest of the page,

00:37:39.424 --> 00:37:42.590
maybe we can leave the alt text empty.

00:37:43.539 --> 00:37:48.234
In this case, you have people's mugshots
with their names.

00:37:48.234 --> 00:37:52.567
If this is useful in the comprehension
of the page,

00:37:53.153 --> 00:37:54.967
you can describe them as well.

00:37:54.967 --> 00:38:00.392
It really depends always
on the experience that you want to give.

00:38:00.392 --> 00:38:01.852
Also, we have different opinions.

00:38:01.852 --> 00:38:07.602
There are people who use screen readers
that are not interested in--

00:38:07.613 --> 00:38:12.696
I recently asked an accessibility
consultant for my website.

00:38:16.756 --> 00:38:20.590
He's a blind user
and he uses screen readers.

00:38:21.445 --> 00:38:24.131
He told me that he was not interested
in the description

00:38:24.131 --> 00:38:26.547
of my personal pictures in the About page,

00:38:26.547 --> 00:38:28.356
for example.

00:38:28.356 --> 00:38:33.308
It's just a matter of preference,
so it's very interesting.

00:38:33.308 --> 00:38:36.141
Also, the gender, race, et cetera.

00:38:37.922 --> 00:38:41.346
Again, if it's relevant
for the content you're writing,

00:38:41.346 --> 00:38:46.346
the place where you put in your image,
let's describe that.

00:38:46.463 --> 00:38:48.047
Marina: Great.

00:38:48.047 --> 00:38:50.547
Okay, next one from Andrew.

00:38:51.622 --> 00:38:54.671
"How far should stand-alone text
for links?

00:38:54.671 --> 00:38:58.563
For example, on a page of names,
should we have a link that reads,

00:38:58.563 --> 00:39:02.039
'Learn more about Joe,
learn more about the sun,'

00:39:02.039 --> 00:39:06.705
et cetera, instead of links
that read, 'Joe, the sun'?"

00:39:07.162 --> 00:39:12.453
Alice: Okay, I imagine that this list
of names should be in a page named,

00:39:12.453 --> 00:39:15.392
for example, Our Team or About page,

00:39:15.392 --> 00:39:19.309
and then a list of all the people
of the team.

00:39:19.332 --> 00:39:24.832
This means that our links
are already placed in a page introduced

00:39:25.039 --> 00:39:29.232
by the word "About" or "Our Team."
The context is clear.

00:39:29.232 --> 00:39:33.934
It's not just a list of links and names
of people without any context.

00:39:33.934 --> 00:39:35.502
How far should we go?

00:39:35.502 --> 00:39:41.335
We should consider the context
of the links where we are seeing them.

00:39:43.956 --> 00:39:48.447
In this case, instead of linking,
"Learn more about Joe,"

00:39:48.447 --> 00:39:51.780
we could link only "About Joe" or "Joe,"

00:39:53.356 --> 00:39:55.862
because it's already clear
that we are speaking about people

00:39:55.862 --> 00:39:58.612
and we are listing them in links.

00:40:00.452 --> 00:40:02.952
Marina: Very interesting, yes.

00:40:03.092 --> 00:40:06.425
Okay, got some anonymous questions here.

00:40:06.891 --> 00:40:10.236
"Can you describe
if there are any big differences

00:40:10.236 --> 00:40:16.075
in what to do for accessibility
on regular web pages versus news posts?

00:40:16.075 --> 00:40:20.964
As far as writing type,
news posts tend to have long sentences,

00:40:20.964 --> 00:40:26.131
headings which have news headlines
versus regular web pages."

00:40:29.644 --> 00:40:30.610
Alice: That's interesting.

00:40:30.610 --> 00:40:34.360
I have not much experience
on news websites,

00:40:35.360 --> 00:40:38.441
but I can imagine
that the same principles apply here.

00:40:38.441 --> 00:40:42.341
If you are talking about a page
to be comprehensible,

00:40:42.341 --> 00:40:48.424
the content is designed to be scannable
by readers at first at a glance.

00:40:51.503 --> 00:40:55.253
I would use the same principle more
or less,

00:40:56.002 --> 00:40:59.168
but I have no much experience in this.

00:40:59.717 --> 00:41:02.133
I hope that the instructions

00:41:02.133 --> 00:41:07.471
that I gave you during this source
can be applicable also to news pages.

00:41:07.471 --> 00:41:11.599
We should prepare a webinar,
especially for that.

00:41:11.599 --> 00:41:12.869
[chuckles]

00:41:12.869 --> 00:41:16.658
Marina: Right,
I think that was a good answer.

00:41:16.658 --> 00:41:23.074
Okay, "Do you have cutlines to enhance
accessibility for images and videos?"

00:41:25.742 --> 00:41:27.587
Alice: Cutlines?

00:41:27.587 --> 00:41:28.862
What does that mean?

00:41:28.862 --> 00:41:30.751
Marina: Cutlines.

00:41:30.751 --> 00:41:32.042
Actually, yes.

00:41:32.042 --> 00:41:36.209
Can anyone in the chat explain
what cutlines are?

00:41:38.456 --> 00:41:39.500
Maybe we can come back to that

00:41:39.500 --> 00:41:41.483
because I don't know
if I've heard it either.

00:41:41.483 --> 00:41:43.513
Oh, captions. That's right.

00:41:43.513 --> 00:41:46.013
Alice: Ah, captions,
Marina: Maybe an older way to say it.

00:41:46.790 --> 00:41:48.453
Alice: Okay, sorry

00:41:48.453 --> 00:41:49.995
Do you use captions to enhance?

00:41:49.995 --> 00:41:51.107
Of course.

00:41:51.107 --> 00:41:54.607
Videos especially as I showed you
on social media

00:41:55.064 --> 00:41:59.648
or web pages in general,
captions are very important.

00:42:01.234 --> 00:42:04.484
Always use them because not everybody--

00:42:05.599 --> 00:42:10.936
Of course, we have the deaf community,
which benefits from captions.

00:42:10.936 --> 00:42:14.035
Also, let's think about all the situations

00:42:14.035 --> 00:42:18.202
when people cannot hear
or listen to your videos.

00:42:19.142 --> 00:42:23.892
It's important to always have captions
on media content.

00:42:29.129 --> 00:42:32.784
Marina: "How do you check if a fancy font
is accessible or not?

00:42:32.784 --> 00:42:37.784
What about fancy fonts
that are available on Google Fonts?"

00:42:38.095 --> 00:42:39.836
Alice: I was referring to fancy fonts

00:42:39.836 --> 00:42:43.920
that you can create
on external font generators.

00:42:45.800 --> 00:42:48.714
I was talking about them especially.

00:42:48.714 --> 00:42:51.714
If you google fancy font generators,

00:42:52.129 --> 00:42:58.329
you will find an incredible list
of many websites doing these decorations,

00:42:58.329 --> 00:43:00.345
creating decoration for fonts.

00:43:00.345 --> 00:43:05.511
In general, Google Fonts are accessible
as per my experience.

00:43:05.930 --> 00:43:09.331
If we choose Google Fonts,
it should be readable.

00:43:09.331 --> 00:43:11.502
It is not a Unicode.

00:43:11.502 --> 00:43:13.132
It's not a Unicode code.

00:43:13.132 --> 00:43:15.084
That's the skimming line.

00:43:15.084 --> 00:43:17.584
That's the differentiation.

00:43:18.374 --> 00:43:21.694
Marina: Got it. We're just going
through these questions rapid-fire.

00:43:21.694 --> 00:43:22.781
Great job

00:43:22.781 --> 00:43:24.807
[laughter]

00:43:24.807 --> 00:43:26.011
Marina: All right.

00:43:26.011 --> 00:43:29.837
Ashley asks, "Is it okay for buttons
to be more general

00:43:29.837 --> 00:43:32.894
like learn more if there is an alt text
on the button

00:43:32.894 --> 00:43:37.644
that is more descriptive
of where the button link goes?"

00:43:37.915 --> 00:43:41.377
Alice: Is it okay for buttons
to be more general like learn more?

00:43:44.855 --> 00:43:49.843
Well, I don't agree with that
because alt text is descriptive.

00:43:49.843 --> 00:43:55.177
The alt text will take its place
in describing the expectations

00:43:56.051 --> 00:43:57.357
when we click on the button,

00:43:57.357 --> 00:44:02.440
but also sighted user need
to have a good reader experience.

00:44:02.565 --> 00:44:08.315
General micro copies for buttons
are not a good practice in general.

00:44:10.204 --> 00:44:13.038
Try to be as specific as possible,

00:44:13.138 --> 00:44:16.471
as clear as possible with plain language

00:44:16.992 --> 00:44:21.418
to respect your readers
in general sighted or not sighted reader.

00:44:21.418 --> 00:44:22.798
It doesn't matter.

00:44:22.798 --> 00:44:27.279
Everybody has the right to be able
to scan a page right away

00:44:27.279 --> 00:44:29.779
and understand its meaning.

00:44:29.816 --> 00:44:33.408
Also, it always depends from the tone
of voice you're using in the content

00:44:33.408 --> 00:44:37.492
and your tone of voice,
your marketing strategy.

00:44:37.514 --> 00:44:40.086
Generally speaking, try to be as specific

00:44:40.086 --> 00:44:43.836
as possible for call to actions
and buttons.

00:44:45.952 --> 00:44:48.452
Marina: Great.

00:44:49.498 --> 00:44:54.002
I don't want to butcher your name,
so I'm not going to say it.

00:44:54.002 --> 00:44:58.252
"Alice, what is a fine balance
per your experience

00:44:58.765 --> 00:45:02.762
and expertise
between aesthetically pleasing design

00:45:02.762 --> 00:45:08.512
where client demands specifics
and those are non-negotiable for them

00:45:09.422 --> 00:45:12.256
or their brand and ensuring a11y?"

00:45:13.914 --> 00:45:15.497
Alice: Accessibility, yes.

00:45:15.497 --> 00:45:16.975
Marina: Accessibility, yes.

00:45:16.975 --> 00:45:19.559
Alice: That's a great question.

00:45:20.197 --> 00:45:23.864
I suggest you
to check Rian Rietveld's talk

00:45:24.973 --> 00:45:30.182
at WordCamp Europe a few months ago
at WordCamp Europe in Torino.

00:45:30.182 --> 00:45:33.978
Rian, who is an incredible WordPress
accessibility specialist,

00:45:33.978 --> 00:45:38.731
gave a talk on this and answered
exactly the same question.

00:45:38.731 --> 00:45:43.981
The balance between aesthetics
and accessibility is a concern,

00:45:44.880 --> 00:45:50.047
but the answer is you can build
and write beautiful websites

00:45:50.721 --> 00:45:52.589
that are also accessible.

00:45:52.589 --> 00:45:57.339
We don't have to sacrifice aesthetics
for accessibility.

00:45:57.761 --> 00:46:01.711
I showed you Piccia Neri's website,
which is amazing.

00:46:01.711 --> 00:46:06.294
It's designed beautifully
and it's totally accessible,

00:46:07.269 --> 00:46:09.769
so you can totally do it.

00:46:10.946 --> 00:46:13.791
The difference is if you have
to convince your customers,

00:46:13.791 --> 00:46:17.791
sometimes this can be a hard point
to overcome.

00:46:20.170 --> 00:46:24.837
In general, if you collect nice use cases
of beautiful,

00:46:25.927 --> 00:46:29.264
accessible websites,
you should have enough material

00:46:29.264 --> 00:46:34.264
to show your clients
that the two things can live together.

00:46:36.092 --> 00:46:41.110
Let's try not to negotiate accessibility
for flashy effects,

00:46:41.110 --> 00:46:46.610
animations, and all the things
that some clients think is a plus.

00:46:46.811 --> 00:46:47.768
It is not.

00:46:47.768 --> 00:46:50.154
We have to demonstrate them

00:46:50.154 --> 00:46:56.071
what happens when an aesthetically
pleasing website is not accessible.

00:46:58.258 --> 00:47:00.271
That should be our selling point

00:47:00.271 --> 00:47:05.355
How many customers we lose
when a website is not accessible.

00:47:05.382 --> 00:47:07.092
It's beautiful but not usable.

00:47:07.092 --> 00:47:09.366
It's beautiful but not accessible.

00:47:09.366 --> 00:47:13.532
That's also a nice selling point
for our clients.

00:47:13.631 --> 00:47:16.131
Marina: Yes, indeed.

00:47:18.469 --> 00:47:23.069
"Do you think sometimes we end up
giving people using screen readers

00:47:23.069 --> 00:47:26.680
for access to content
rather than equal access?

00:47:26.680 --> 00:47:30.589
How do you try to provide equal access
to everyone?

00:47:30.589 --> 00:47:36.922
Alt text may give non-sighted users
more information than sighted readers."

00:47:38.941 --> 00:47:40.406
Alice: This is a nice question.

00:47:40.406 --> 00:47:46.322
I think that all the visual information
we get when we scan a website,

00:47:46.930 --> 00:47:48.830
when we navigate through web pages,

00:47:48.830 --> 00:47:50.821
so the visual inputs that we get,

00:47:50.821 --> 00:47:54.655
the audio inputs
that we get are information.

00:47:55.608 --> 00:47:59.775
There's no real imbalance
if we write accessibly.

00:47:59.977 --> 00:48:04.043
There shouldn't be this imbalance
between sighted user

00:48:04.043 --> 00:48:06.876
and people with visual impairment.

00:48:09.582 --> 00:48:12.796
We can find the right balance, I think.

00:48:12.796 --> 00:48:15.031
Let's just think
that all the things that we can see

00:48:15.031 --> 00:48:17.865
and hear are added-up information.

00:48:18.575 --> 00:48:20.570
There should be no real difference.

00:48:20.570 --> 00:48:25.404
I don't know if I was clear,
if I answered your question.

00:48:28.972 --> 00:48:32.977
Marina: I think someone had asked
if you could repeat the name of the--

00:48:32.977 --> 00:48:36.954
was it the Pictionary website
that you gave as an example

00:48:36.954 --> 00:48:40.204
or if you gave a website as an example?

00:48:42.894 --> 00:48:44.076
Alice: Ah, Piccia.

00:48:44.076 --> 00:48:45.216
Piccia Neri.

00:48:45.216 --> 00:48:46.679
It's on my slides.

00:48:46.679 --> 00:48:49.846
You can find them linked to my slides.

00:48:50.219 --> 00:48:52.719
Marina: Okay, great.

00:48:54.259 --> 00:48:56.454
We have about two more minutes.

00:48:56.454 --> 00:48:59.836
Kayla asked, "We have stopped
using Read More buttons because

00:48:59.836 --> 00:49:02.433
that text is not helpful
like you talked about.

00:49:02.433 --> 00:49:05.356
What about linking to portfolio pieces
or case studies,

00:49:05.356 --> 00:49:08.776
for example, that have an image,
heading, and a button

00:49:08.776 --> 00:49:11.549
The heading and image give context
where the button will go,

00:49:11.549 --> 00:49:13.867
but the button just says, 'Get details.'

00:49:13.867 --> 00:49:20.061
Is that text also too vague even
with the context of the heading before it?

00:49:20.061 --> 00:49:24.351
We want it to be actionable
to get people to click on these items."

00:49:24.351 --> 00:49:26.851
Alice: If this general text

00:49:27.219 --> 00:49:31.136
is well-placed in the context
of the web page,

00:49:31.198 --> 00:49:35.281
we don't have to demonize
all general microcopy.

00:49:36.213 --> 00:49:41.296
If it's readable and useful,
it's okay also if it's general.

00:49:42.606 --> 00:49:48.273
My point was let's build the whole context
of the web page in order

00:49:48.527 --> 00:49:51.418
for buttons to be useful and meaningful.

00:49:51.418 --> 00:49:55.579
If you already have a heading
and an image giving context

00:49:55.579 --> 00:49:56.945
and you wrote the alt text

00:49:56.945 --> 00:50:00.612
and all the language
of your page is clear,

00:50:01.269 --> 00:50:03.769
you can have a general button.

00:50:03.957 --> 00:50:08.957
It's not a strict rule,
but I hope it's clear what I meant.

00:50:09.691 --> 00:50:11.349
Get details.

00:50:11.349 --> 00:50:14.849
It can be okay if the context is coherent.

00:50:17.249 --> 00:50:18.490
Marina: Great.

